  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Choose Napa for Structure, Sonoma for Elegance</strong> - When selecting between regions, understand that Napa Valley's warmer climate and volcanic soils produce Cabernets with more concentrated tannins and higher alcohol (often 14.5-15.5%), while Sonoma's cooler coastal influence and diverse soils create wines with better natural acidity and more restrained alcohol levels (13.5-14.5%). This makes Napa wines ideal for special occasions requiring power, while Sonoma excels for food pairing versatility.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Sonoma Cooler Than Napa</strong> - Due to their structural differences, serve Sonoma Cabernets at 62-65°F to preserve their elegant fruit expression and natural acidity, while Napa Cabernets benefit from slightly warmer serving temperatures of 65-68°F to soften their more robust tannin structure and showcase their concentrated dark fruit character.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Napa Longer, Sonoma Less</strong> - Young Napa Cabernets (under 8 years) typically require 2-3 hours of decanting to integrate their powerful tannins and high-extract character. Sonoma Cabernets need only 30-60 minutes, as their naturally softer tannin profile and integrated structure can become over-aerated with excessive decanting, losing their signature finesse.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Bordeaux Glasses for Both, But Consider Bowl Size</strong> - While both regions benefit from large Bordeaux-style glasses, choose slightly larger bowls (22-24oz) for Napa wines to accommodate their higher alcohol and concentrate aromatics, and medium bowls (18-20oz) for Sonoma wines to focus their more subtle, terroir-driven characteristics without overwhelming the palate.</li>

  <li><strong>Napa Ages Longer, Sonoma Drinks Earlier</strong> - Napa Valley Cabernets from top producers like Screaming Eagle or Harlan Estate can age gracefully for 20-30 years due to their high tannin and acid backbone, while most Sonoma Cabernets from regions like Alexander Valley or Dry Creek reach peak drinking between 8-15 years, though premium Sonoma Mountain wines can age longer due to elevation and cooler temperatures.</li>

  <li><strong>Peak Drinking Windows Differ by Subregion</strong> - Rutherford and Oakville Napa Cabernets hit their stride at 10-12 years when their dusty tannins integrate, while Sonoma Coast Cabernets are approachable at 5-7 years due to their naturally softer extraction. However, Alexander Valley wines need 6-8 years to resolve their more structured tannins from warmer vineyard sites.</li>

  <li><strong>Vintage Variation Impacts Sonoma More</strong> - Sonoma's proximity to the Pacific Ocean makes it more susceptible to vintage variation from marine influence and fog patterns. Cool years like 2010 or 2011 produce more austere Sonoma wines that need extra aging, while warm years create immediately approachable styles. Napa's more continental climate provides greater vintage consistency.</li>

  <li><strong>Food Pairing Strategy Differs by Region</strong> - Napa's higher tannin and alcohol content pairs excellently with rich, fatty meats like ribeye or duck confit, while Sonoma's higher acidity and more moderate alcohol makes it superior with herb-crusted lamb, mushroom dishes, or aged cheeses where you want the wine to complement rather than overpower the food's nuanced flavors.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the main difference between Sonoma and Napa Valley wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley focuses heavily on Cabernet Sauvignon and tends toward riper, more concentrated wines with higher alcohol levels, while Sonoma County offers greater diversity with cooler-climate varieties like Pinot Noir and Chardonnay alongside warmer-climate reds. Sonoma's proximity to the Pacific Ocean creates more varied microclimates, resulting in wines with higher acidity and more restrained fruit character compared to Napa's typically bold, opulent style.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which region offers better value for money - Sonoma or Napa?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sonoma generally offers superior value, with excellent wines starting around $25-40 compared to Napa's entry point of $50-75 for comparable quality. This price difference stems from Napa's prestige factor and limited land availability, while Sonoma's larger size and diverse appellations provide more options at accessible price points. You'll find outstanding Sonoma Pinot Noir and Chardonnay that compete with wines costing twice as much from Napa.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should wine beginners start with Sonoma or Napa wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Beginners should start with Sonoma wines because they typically show better balance, food-friendliness, and represent classic varietal character without overwhelming intensity. Sonoma's cooler-climate wines have more approachable acidity and alcohol levels (13-14% vs. Napa's 14.5-16%), making them easier to appreciate while learning. The region's diversity also allows newcomers to explore different styles - from crisp Russian River Chardonnay to elegant Sonoma Coast Pinot Noir.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose between a Sonoma and Napa Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Choose Napa Cabernet if you prefer powerful, concentrated wines with dark fruit flavors, higher tannins, and bold oak influence - ideal for special occasions or aging. Opt for Sonoma Cabernet when you want more food-friendly wines with better balance, brighter acidity, and more restrained fruit character that pairs well with everyday meals. Sonoma versions typically cost 30-50% less while offering excellent quality from appellations like Alexander Valley and Dry Creek Valley.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when comparing Sonoma vs Napa wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is assuming Napa is automatically superior due to its reputation and higher prices. Many wine drinkers overlook Sonoma's exceptional cool-climate varietals like Pinot Noir and Chardonnay, where the region often outperforms Napa due to better suited terroir. Another common error is not recognizing that Sonoma County encompasses 18 distinct AVAs with dramatically different styles, from the foggy Sonoma Coast to the warm Alexander Valley.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which region's wines age better - Sonoma or Napa?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Both regions produce age-worthy wines, but they age differently: Napa Cabernets often have more aging potential due to higher tannin levels and concentration, developing complex tertiary flavors over 15-25 years. Sonoma wines typically reach their peak sooner (5-15 years) but maintain elegance and freshness longer due to higher natural acidity. For Pinot Noir and Chardonnay, Sonoma's cooler climate actually provides superior aging potential with better acid structure.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good alternatives to expensive Napa Valley wines from Sonoma?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely - Sonoma's Alexander Valley produces Cabernets that rival Napa at half the price, while Dry Creek Valley Zinfandels offer similar power and complexity to Napa's cult Zins. For Bordeaux-style blends, look to Sonoma's Red Hills or Bennett Valley, where producers like Laurel Glen and Matanzas Creek create wines comparable to $100+ Napa offerings for $40-60. Russian River Valley Pinot Noir consistently outperforms Napa's attempts at this variety.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do serving temperatures differ between Sonoma and Napa wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sonoma wines generally benefit from slightly cooler serving temperatures due to their higher acidity and more delicate fruit expression - serve reds at 60-62°F versus 62-65°F for Napa reds. Sonoma's cool-climate whites (Chardonnay, Sauvignon Blanc) show best at 45-50°F to preserve their crisp minerality, while Napa whites can handle 50-55°F. The key is that Sonoma's more restrained style requires cooler temperatures to highlight its subtle nuances and prevent the alcohol from dominating.</p>
